# CUDA-Q Accelerates Quantum Workloads at GTC 2026

Over the past year the quantum computing industry has shifted from qubit demonstrations to the work of building large-scale quantum-classical supercomputers. Central to that transition has been the intersection of quantum computing work with AI supercomputing. At GTC 2026, researchers and developers across the ecosystem are demonstrating how the NVIDIA [CUDA-Q](https://developer.nvidia.com/cuda-q) platform is bringing accelerated computing to the key workloads set to define quantum computing in 2026 and beyond. 

<figure markdown="1">
![CUDAQ GTC26 Quantum Workloads](../../../images/cudaq-blog-gtc26/cudaq_blog_hero_image.png){ width="800" }
</figure>

<!-- more -->

---

## Quantum Application Development

Building better quantum algorithms remains a critical workload for shortening the timeline to utility-scale quantum computing. GPU-accelerated simulation is the central tool for exploring and refining these algorithms, and teams around the world are continuing to push applications work to new levels with CUDA-Q's access to GPU-accelerated simulations.

[CINECA](https://www.cineca.it/en) and [Kipu Quantum](https://www.kipu-quantum.com/) have [run what is believed to be the largest-known **statevector simulation** of a quantum optimization routine](https://kipu-quantum.com/knowledge-hub/news/kipu-nvidia-hybrid-optimization-simulation/) — a 43-qubit simulation of a novel **Quantum-Enhanced Memetic Tabu Search (QE-MTS)** algorithm on 2,048 NVIDIA Ampere GPUs. QE-MTS targets **Low Autocorrelation Binary Sequence (LABS)** problems, a challenging class of combinatorial optimization with applications in signal processing and communications.

[Infleqtion](https://www.infleqtion.com/) is [applying CUDA-Q to biomarker discovery through its **Q4Bio** project](http://infleqtion.com/gpu-quantum-biomarker-discovery), using **quantum neural networks** to identify high-impact feature sets from complex cancer data. The team has consumed 24,000 NVIDIA A100 GPU-node-hours on the Perlmutter supercomputer at NERSC to train these networks. Infleqtion uses a hybrid combination of its Sqale QPU and NVIDIA GPUs for inference, and is exploring [NVIDIA NVQLink](https://www.nvidia.com/en-us/solutions/quantum-computing/nvqlink/) to scale execution further.

<figure markdown="1">
![Hypergraph of interactions in Infleqtion Work](../../../images/cudaq-blog-gtc26/infleqtion_image.png){ width="500" }
</figure>

_Fig 1: Hypergraph showing interactions between logical qubits in Infleqtion's demonstration of quantum neural networks_

A collaboration between [UCL](https://www.ucl.ac.uk/), [QMatter](https://qmatter.xyz/), the [Technical University of Munich](https://www.tum.de/en/), [Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München](https://www.lmu.de/en/), [LRZ](https://www.lrz.de/en/), and [IQM](https://www.meetiqm.com/) [demonstrated a hybrid biomolecular simulation of a **G-protein-coupled receptor (GPCR)**](https://qmatter.xyz/where-quantum-computing-meets-gpu-accelerated-supercomputing/) on the CUDA-Q platform, with the quantum component executed on Euro-Q-Exa — an IQM 54-qubit system, alongside NVIDIA H100 GPUs hosted at the LRZ AI cluster. The postprocessing element of the work was further scaled to a billion quantum configurations using 1,200 NVIDIA H100 on the [Eos](https://blogs.nvidia.com/blog/eos/) cluster

<figure markdown="1">
![GPCR Protein from Qmatter Work](../../../images/cudaq-blog-gtc26/qmatter_GPCR.png){ width="800" }
</figure>

_Fig 2: GPCR protein active site modelled in collaboration between UCL, QMatter, TUM, LMU, LRZ and IQM_

