## Quantum Error Correction 

CUDA-Q is also proving essential for research into quantum error correction — work critical to the long-term viability of quantum computing.

Researchers at the [University of Edinburgh](https://www.ed.ac.uk/), working through the Grace Hopper Superchip Seed Program with [Supermicro](https://www.supermicro.com/), have [performed breakthrough work by developing a **vibe decoder** for color codes](https://qec.codes/blog/vibe_gpu/). By combining an ensemble of **Belief Propagation (BP)** decoders parallelized with CUDA on NVIDIA GH200 GPUs, vibe decoding achieves microsecond per-round batched throughput — 900x faster than previous state-of-the-art — providing the most compelling evidence yet that color code decoding could compete with industry-standard surface codes.



[Alice & Bob](https://www.alice-bob.com/) are using CUDA-Q's GPU acceleration to [run noisy simulations validating **elevator codes**](https://alice-bob.com/blog/how-alice-bob-uses-nvidia-cuda-q-to-accelerate-quantum-error-correction-research), a new error correction code designed for the biased noise in their cat qubits. The team benchmarked a 9.25x speedup over CPU-based techniques when decoding a $[15,9,3]$, $d_z=9$ elevator code from 100,000 simulated shots on an NVIDIA GH200.

---

## Quantum-Classical Integrations

Providing developers the tools they need to work with future quantum-GPU supercomputers is key to advancing quantum computing. Quantum software builders are drawing on CUDA-Q to ensure their tools seamlessly support hybrid systems.

[Scaleway](https://www.scaleway.com/) now supports CUDA-Q kernels from its Quantum-as-a-Service platform, with execution across hardware from [Alpine Quantum Technologies](https://www.aqt.eu/), while [PsiQuantum](https://www.psiquantum.com/) has [integrated CUDA-Q with PsiQuantum Construct](https://www.psiquantum.com/news-import/construct-nvidia-cudaq) for simulating large-scale, fault-tolerant hybrid applications. 

[TII](https://www.tii.ae/) has integrated its Qibo framework with CUDA-Q for hybrid workload validation - planning to use NVQLink in future work, and [Pasqal](https://www.pasqal.com/) has [integrated CUDA-Q with its **Quantum Resource Management Interface (QRMI)** runtime](https://www.pasqal.com/newsroom/pasqal-introduces-new-integration-with-nvidia-cuda-q-to-enhance-its-hybrid-quantum-computing-environment-for-hpc/), enabling SLURM-based scheduling of work across Pasqal QPUs and accelerated computing. 

Meanwhile [memQ](https://memq.tech/) [announced its Extensible Distributed Quantum Compiler (xDQC)](https://memq.tech/memq_qc_software_stack) built on CUDA-Q, demonstrating how hybrid applications can be spread across multi-QPU systems - simulating hundreds of qubits across eight QPUs, and HPE has [incorporated NVQLink into its vision for quantum supercomputing](https://community.hpe.com/t5/advancing-life-work/toward-a-utility-scale-quantum-supercomputer-with-tight-hpc-qc/ba-p/7262995).


---

## AI-Powered Quantum Development

Quantum researchers are looking to the latest AI advances and CUDA-Q is establishing itself as the backbone for AI-driven quantum development - making quantum algorithm and hardware design faster and more accessible.

[Hiverge](https://www.hiverge.com/) has [integrated CUDA-Q with **the Hive**](https://hiverge.ai/blog/quantinuum-nvidia-collaboration), an AI platform that uses LLM agents to translate natural-language problem descriptions into executable quantum circuits. [Quantinuum](https://www.quantinuum.com/) is using the Hive for AI-guided discovery of quantum algorithms for combinatorial optimization, with applications in power grid dispatch, nuclear fuel arrangement, and molecular design for drug and materials discovery. 

[QCentroid](https://www.qcentroid.xyz/) has [integrated CUDA-Q with its **QuantumOps** platform](https://qcentroid.xyz/news/qcentroid-makes-nvidia-cuda-q-available-in-its-quantumops-platform-to-accelerate-enterprise-hybrid-quantum-adoption/), giving enterprise users access through an AI copilot layer. And [Conductor Quantum](https://www.conductorquantum.com/) announced Coda's new **Model Context Protocol (MCP)**, which gives AI agents access to quantum compute resources as tools — supporting CUDA-Q transpilation from other frameworks and circuit simulations of up to 34 qubits for autonomous debugging and optimization.

